See the table, Introd. . xxxi. p The four genera are given within a single verse by Virgil, Aen. vi 733 ‘hinc metuunt cupiuntque, dolent gaudent- que’ and by Horace, Ep. i 6, 12 ‘gau- deat an doleat, cupiat metuatne‚ quid ad rem?' partibusz the sub-divisions of a genus are usually called partes in Cicero, who rejected species. Varro and Silver Age writers have the latter term in this sense. Cicero also employs the term formae. Cf. v 25, 71 ‘genera partesque uirtutum’3 de Inu. i 22, 3² ‘genus est quod plures partes amplectitur, ut animal. pars est, quae subest generi, ut equus'; Topica 6——7‚ 50—-31 ‘nolim enim, ne si Latine quidem possit dici, specierum et speciebus dicere3 ...formis et formarum uelim.’ cum omnis perturbatio sit: see Zeno's definition in iv 6, 1 1 n. on ‘haec definitio, ut.'
